hashicorp/raft provides the consensus layer. You provide the state machine:

```go
// Your FSM implements three methods:
type KVStore struct {
    data map[string]string
    mu   sync.RWMutex
}

// Apply - called when Raft commits a log entry
func (k *KVStore) Apply(log *raft.Log) interface{} {
    var cmd Command
    json.Unmarshal(log.Data, &cmd)
    k.mu.Lock()
    defer k.mu.Unlock()
    switch cmd.Op {
    case "set":
        k.data[cmd.Key] = cmd.Value
    case "delete":
        delete(k.data, cmd.Key)
    }
    return nil
}

// Snapshot - for compacting the log
func (k *KVStore) Snapshot() (raft.FSMSnapshot, error) { ... }

// Restore - rebuild state from snapshot
func (k *KVStore) Restore(rc io.ReadCloser) error { ... }
```

**Write path**: Client -> Leader -> `raft.Apply(command)` -> Raft replicates to majority -> `FSM.Apply()` called on all nodes -> Response to client.

**Read path**: Can read from leader (strong consistency) or any node (eventual consistency).

You get: leader election, log replication, membership changes, snapshotting. All for free. You just implement the state machine.
